<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-978-618  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 978 618.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Digital Review  Dec 18 1989 v6 n50 p3(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Testing software simulates use of VAX applications. (PerformanceSoftware V-Test) (product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Smalley, Eric.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Performance Software Inc. (Newbury, Massachusetts) (productintroduction).andO;Product:   V-Test (Performance analysis software) (product introduction).andO;Topic:     Capacity ManagementSimulation of Computer SystemsSoftware PackagesTestingProduct Introduction.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Testing Software Simulates Use of VAX ApplicationsandM;LONDON -- Performance Software has released capacity-testing software for VMSthat simulates users running application software.andM;V-Test, scheduled foravailability in the United States next month, allowssytem managers to construct tests that simulate terminal operators on VAXsystems.andP;  The software can be used to test applications or hardware,according to Performance Software Managing Director, Tom Hankinson.andM;V-Test simulates operators processing applications and can be set with delaysto reflect operator thinking time and typing speed, according to companyofficials.andM;V-Test incorporates an editor and compiler for developing scripts, a scriptlibrary and a utility for running the scripts.andM;V-Test records the system activity and provides analysis of the systemperformance.andM;The software can also be used by developers to ensure compatibility betweendifferent versions of their products, officials said.andM;Scripts can include recordings of live operator sessions as well as writtensimulations.andP;  The scripts, appearing to the VAX system as real operators atreal terminals, can be executed from virtual terminals or real terminalconnections, the officials said.andM;V-Test supports VMS SMP and VAXcluster systems.andM;It is based in part on Performance Software's Systelon-line-transaction-processing application development environment and videoremote terminal-monitoring software.andM;In addition to the terminal-session recorder, script language and variablespeed control, V-Test includes randomized input lists, a run-time controllerand statistical data analyzer.andM;V-Test is priced according to CPU size, ranging from $8,000 to $40,000.andM;The company's U.S.andP;  subsidiary, Performance Software Inc., can be contactedat The Carriage House, 28 Green St., Newbury, MA 01951, (800) 873-6587 or(508) 462-0737.andO;</TEXT></DOC>